      <hedline>
        <hl1>Mideast Turmoil Is Like No Other</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>George Stack letter contends America does not base its hope for peace in Middle East upon a misunderstanding of Islamic faith or culture (Oct 14 Op-Ed by Reuel Marc Gerecht)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Price of America's Naivete,'' by Reuel Marc Gerecht (Op-Ed, Oct. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Price of America's Naivete,'' by Reuel Marc Gerecht (Op-Ed, Oct. 14):</p>
        <p>America does not base its hope for peace in the Middle East upon a misunderstanding of Islamic faith or culture. We tempt the region with our vocabulary of tolerance, moderation, empathy and compromise because we know that peace is within reach despite the long history of animosities in the region.</p>
        <p>This vocabulary embodies the hope that each side will enhance its own view of the region by considering the other's history, culture and faith-based needs. In pursuing peace, we are sophisticated when we presuppose a rise above parochialism.</p>
        <p>GEORGE STACK  Great Neck, N.Y., Oct. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
